#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:1
msgid "`?` in `main` and tests"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.26](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.26-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust's error handling revolves around returning `Result<T, E>` and using `?` "
"to propagate errors. For those who write many small programs and, hopefully, "
"many tests, one common paper cut has been mixing entry points such as `main` "
"and `#[test]`s with error handling."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:10
msgid "As an example, you might have tried to write:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:16
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:29
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:70
msgid "\"bar.txt\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:20
msgid ""
"Since `?` works by propagating the `Result` with an early return to the "
"enclosing function, the snippet above does not work, and results today in "
"the following error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:36
msgid ""
"To solve this problem in Rust 2015, you might have written something like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:39
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:45
msgid "// real logic..\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:51
msgid "\"Application error: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:57
msgid ""
"However, in this case, the `run` function has all the interesting logic and "
"`main` is just boilerplate. The problem is even worse for `#[test]`s, since "
"there tend to be a lot more of them."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:61
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018 you can instead let your `#[test]`s and `main` functions return "
"a `Result`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:65
msgid "// Rust 2018\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:76
msgid ""
"In this case, if say the file doesn't exist and there is an `Err(err)` "
"somewhere, then `main` will exit with an error code (not `0`) and print out "
"a `Debug` representation of `err`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:80
msgid "More details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:82
msgid ""
"Getting `-> Result<..>` to work in the context of `main` and `#[test]`s is "
"not magic. It is all backed up by a `Termination` trait which all valid "
"return types of `main` and testing functions must implement. The trait is "
"defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:92
msgid ""
"When setting up the entry point for your application, the compiler will use "
"this trait and call `.report()` on the `Result` of the `main` function you "
"have written."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:95
msgid ""
"Two simplified example implementations of this trait for `Result` and `()` "
"are:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:116
msgid "\"Error: {:?}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:125
msgid ""
"As you can see in the case of `()`, a success code is simply returned. In "
"the case of `Result`, the success case delegates to the implementation for "
"`()` but prints out an error message and a failure exit code on `Err(..)`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/question-mark-in-main-and-tests.md:129
msgid ""
"To learn more about the finer details, consult either [the tracking issue]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/43301) or [the RFC](https://github."
"com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/1937-ques-in-main.md)."
msgstr ""
